Ghana-born actor Kobna Holdbrook-Smith won the best actor prize at London’s prestigious Oliver Awards for his lead role in a musical about the life of Tina Turner. Holdbrook-Smith plays her husband Ike Turner. The Olivier Awards celebrate the best performances in London’s theatres. Accepting the award, an emotional Holdbrook-Smith thanked “all my family in Ghana”. Holdbrook-Smith was born in Accra, Ghana. He grew up in Frimley Surrey, England, went to school in Frimley, with his mother Tenu, his father Henry and brother Kofi. Komla Dumor: Exit of ‘a star from the start’ Ghana mourns Komla Dumor Ghana court frees ‘Boko Haram’ film producer